\par June 21, 43

\par Awoke this morning at 6:30 A.M. with general alarm. I found out that thirty Jap planes were seen over Cactus coming in our direction. All 32 fighters were launched and flew all day, stopping just long enough to refuel and change pilots.

\par I flew from 1430 to 1745 and landed aboard after sunset. We saw a couple of Jap bombers, but they had more altitude and we couldn\rquote t catch them even after dropping our wing tanks.

\par We have old planes off the Enterprise and Saratoga, and we shouldn\rquote t even be in the combat zone with them. The engines have all but worn out completely. They say a good pilot can fly the crates the planes come in. But for my personal money I

\rquote ll fly the crates they come in \endash  (that is if I had the rank to choose between them). Every day we have an average of seven forced landin

gs abord carrier because of mechanical failure. Right now this is a military secret, but the day will come when the men back home will put out a plane that will be new and strong to best the Jap. So until that day, we will trudge along with what little ma

terial we have and help of God.

\par 

\par -------------------------------------------------------------

\par July 4, 1943

\par Dear Mom and Dad:

\par \'85 Yesterday I developed an oil leak in my plane, and had to come 150 miles on ten lbs. oil pressure back to base. I got home with two gallons of oil and when I left the oil tank held eleven gallons. The Line officer said. \'93

Another 20 minutes in the air and your engine would have frozen up completely.\'94

\par \'93So, mother, that is one time your little boy cheated the old man out of crossing my name from his book.\'94

\par Today, I took of out off out of gas on my wing tank and had to return to base.

\par Two days ago a fellow named Ensign Fitzpatrick had to make a forced landing two miles off shore; so when he finally made land in the rubber boat; he camped

 out over night. When darkness came on, he shot tracer bullets into the air out of his forty-five. Next morning he was picked up by a coast watch who saw tracers in the dark and heard accompanying shots.

\par Also two days ago eight of our boys took off Grummin

 wildcats and went over Lunda they were attacked by thirty-five zeros. One of the boys named Lt. (J.G.) Woods never came back and I believe never will. Five out of the eight came back and they all had a few zeroes. The count was three of ours to nine our 

theirs. 

\par Probably by the time I send this letter I will have a few zeros to my credits (I\rquote ll soon see)

\par We had a raid last night and we all crowded down in our fox hole. Only six bombs dropped and they were all near the runway. Not much damage was done.

\par We have a movie here every night but most of the time we see it I shifts/ You know between one \'93Condition Red\'94 to another. Maybe in a year we can see some good Jap movies in Tokyo theatres.

\par Take good care and don\rquote t worry about me, I\rquote m happy and contented. Your loving son and overseas fighter pilot \endash  Boots

\par 

\par 

\par PS. Today was the day for fireworks! We flew C.A.P. over Lunda like I said, and we saw fifteen Jap Bettys (bombers) come in and drop bombs on Rendevo Harbor and ships inside harbor. We were two miles away an

d 2000 feet lower than they, and all we could do was watch the fight. I saw AA fire hit one bomber squarely and when it flew up, it also caught two more bombers in explosion. They were on each side and it was fine to see all three go down in flame. But th

e action became terrific \endash  the other flight of Grummen wildcats and marine F4U\rquote 

s came in from above and shot down more. Just below us there was a fight and when we went into a dive we saw two zeros flaming and also one Grumman. I did not fire a shot and did

 not get one bullet hole in plane; but I sure did see a fine show. I made a forced landing back at field with five gallons of gasoline.

\par I can remember when I was a little boy and went to the fair and saw fireworks. but today was the best of my life. I just couldn\rquote t help thinking that every sky rocket and every flame was ignited to kill human life by human life.

\par \tab \tab \tab Your wiser and more experienced son who thinks of home more very day.

\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab Boots

