I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \expnd0\expndtw-4\cf1\insrsid5243573 was still on my way back from water experience }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \expnd0\expndtw-3\cf1\insrsid5243573 by destroyer, When I got back I waited

 anxiously for their return.  Out of 32 planes only 22 planes and pilots came back. Some where seen shot down, some were seen in water in rubber boats. Our score was fifteen zeros to ten Grummens, which we knew wasn\rquote 

t too good. But the bombers sunk a cruiser, two destroyers and bombed field.

\par The next raid we went on was a complete success. We lost one pilot and plane through accident. Two of our planes came together in air over Kahili when a wingman turned nose upward to shoot at a zero. The leader finally 

returned to Sagi and bailed out, the wingman just went down ay Kahili; and is probably now a Japanese prisoner.

\par When we were on the raid we could see about 50- or 60 zeros above us and one would dive down and then pull sharply out of our gun fire. They wou

ld not attack us though because they did not have us at three to one odds like they usually did in a fight. Our bombers wrecked the place; so they had to spend a few days digging out of the ruins.

\par 

\par ___________________________________

\par July 21, 1943

\par At three

 in the afternoon, Lt. (J.G.) Tavernetti with Kukuk as wingman and Allan other wingman strafed Bairiki Harbor. When we dove over harbor we saw about 18 Japs in swimming. We opened up our guns and watched them scamper. I guess we killed a few in the water,

 and we also strafed a few landing barrages. The woods was full of Japs; so we knew our stray bullets massacred many a yellow bodies from Tokyo.

